Chris Grabenstein has received
many awards including the Agatha

00:00:35.700 --> 00:00:38.900
Award for Best Children's and
Young Adult Novels four times,

00:00:38.900 --> 00:00:40.810
and from what I can tell,

00:00:40.810 --> 00:00:43.750
he also has a wickedly
fun sense of humor.

00:00:43.750 --> 00:00:46.070
His newest book is
Welcome to Wonderland,

00:00:46.070 --> 00:00:47.550
Sandapalooza Shake-Up,

00:00:47.550 --> 00:00:50.650
and he also has a really
big surprise for you guys.

00:00:50.650 --> 00:00:52.230
You're going to want to
stick around for this.

00:00:52.230 --> 00:00:55.770
He's going to be signing
at 1:00 over in line 14.

00:00:55.770 --> 00:00:57.070
Please welcome, Chris
Grabenstein.

00:00:57.070 --> 00:00:58.370
&gt;&gt; Chris Grabenstein: Thank you.

00:00:58.370 --> 00:01:01.530
&gt;&gt; Jill Garcia: You're welcome.

00:01:01.530 --> 00:01:03.010
&gt;&gt; Chris Grabenstein:
Thank you so much.

00:01:03.010 --> 00:01:04.610
Thank you guys for coming out.

00:01:04.610 --> 00:01:06.950
It's great to be here
in our nation's capital.

00:01:06.950 --> 00:01:09.590
They put my slide up on
the, I need my slides now.

00:01:09.590 --> 00:01:11.720
Okay. Do we have any fifth
graders here in the audience?

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:13.020
Any fifth graders.

00:01:13.020 --> 00:01:16.990
Up on that screen
right now is my picture

00:01:16.990 --> 00:01:20.050
when I was in the fifth grade.

00:01:20.050 --> 00:01:21.570
Have any of you been able
to figure out which one

00:01:21.570 --> 00:01:24.830
of those kids I was when
I was in the fifth grade?

00:01:24.830 --> 00:01:27.630
Anybody want to guess
who thinks they know?

00:01:27.630 --> 00:01:28.930
Yes, which one was I?

00:01:28.930 --> 00:01:31.920
&gt;&gt; On the top row.

00:01:31.920 --> 00:01:33.220
&gt;&gt; Chris Grabenstein: Top row.

00:01:33.220 --> 00:01:35.070
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:01:35.070 --> 00:01:36.370
On this side.

00:01:36.370 --> 00:01:37.670
Oh, the guy with the blond hair?

00:01:37.670 --> 00:01:38.970
No, his hair is blond.

00:01:38.970 --> 00:01:40.660
What color is my hair?

00:01:40.660 --> 00:01:43.050
[ Inaudible Comments ]

00:01:43.050 --> 00:01:45.480
What color did my
hair used to be.

00:01:45.480 --> 00:01:47.560
Black. It used to be black,
so you're looking for someone

00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:49.350
with black hair up there.

00:01:49.350 --> 00:01:51.510
Yes, which one was I?

00:01:51.510 --> 00:01:54.040
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:55.520
The second row in the
little turtle neck.

00:01:55.520 --> 00:01:58.370
He's got a receding hairline,
looks like he's going bald?

00:01:58.370 --> 00:01:59.670
No, it's not me.

00:01:59.670 --> 00:02:01.770
I didn't start going bald
until like ten years ago.

00:02:01.770 --> 00:02:04.310
That kid was going bald
in the fifth grade.

00:02:04.310 --> 00:02:05.850
By the time we got
to sixth grade,

00:02:05.850 --> 00:02:08.390
we all called him Chrome Dome.

00:02:08.390 --> 00:02:10.310
Now since I mostly
write mysteries,

00:02:10.310 --> 00:02:12.810
I'm going to give you
guys a clue right now.

00:02:12.810 --> 00:02:14.750
When I was in fifth grade,

00:02:14.750 --> 00:02:17.570
my eyesight was better
than it is today.

00:02:17.570 --> 00:02:20.570
I did not wear glasses when
I was in the fifth grade.

00:02:20.570 --> 00:02:21.990
Who seems to know?

00:02:21.990 --> 00:02:23.290
Yes, which one was I?

00:02:23.290 --> 00:02:25.290
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:02:25.290 --> 00:02:27.590
The one in the red T-shirt?

00:02:27.590 --> 00:02:31.180
Oh the one T-shirt,
no his hair is blond.

00:02:31.180 --> 00:02:33.990
Have any of you read
any of my books?

00:02:33.990 --> 00:02:37.120
Has anybody here
read one of my books.

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:39.250
I'm giving you another
clue right now.

00:02:39.250 --> 00:02:42.210
Have you read my books?

00:02:42.210 --> 00:02:44.570
Yes, the young man
in the red shirt.

00:02:44.570 --> 00:02:47.590
Which one do you think I am?

00:02:47.590 --> 00:02:49.000
The one in the red shirt.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:51.130
Yes. That was me
in the fifth grade.

00:02:51.130 --> 00:02:54.510
Let's give this guy
a round of applause.

00:02:54.510 --> 00:02:57.060
So I show you that picture
for a couple reasons.

00:02:57.060 --> 00:03:00.320
One, to prove before my
hair started going gray,

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:01.620
thank you very much
for notice that.

00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:04.180
Before it started going
backwards on my head,

00:03:04.180 --> 00:03:07.670
I was actually at one point
in my life 10 years old

00:03:07.670 --> 00:03:10.220
and in the fifth grade,
and in the fifth grade is

00:03:10.220 --> 00:03:12.360
when I first started
having fun writing.

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:13.890
I used to do these
little comic books

00:03:13.890 --> 00:03:15.840
where I'd draw the pictures
and make up the stories

00:03:15.840 --> 00:03:17.290
and pass them out to my friends.

00:03:17.290 --> 00:03:18.590
And when I was in fifth grade,

00:03:18.590 --> 00:03:20.810
I grew up in a little town
called Signal Mountain,

00:03:20.810 --> 00:03:23.680
Tennessee, which is outside
of Chattanooga, Tennessee,

00:03:23.680 --> 00:03:26.900
and the local Lions Club had
an essay writing contest.

00:03:26.900 --> 00:03:29.800
I entered and won first prize.

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:31.700
That was my first
writing award ever.

00:03:31.700 --> 00:03:33.790
It was a cream puff
day in our house.

00:03:33.790 --> 00:03:36.290
Then I went to Junior
High School,

00:03:36.290 --> 00:03:38.720
and I got the bowl
haircut going guys.

00:03:38.720 --> 00:03:40.020
I recommend that look.

00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:41.320
It's a good look.

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:42.620
You just put a bowl
on your head.

00:03:42.620 --> 00:03:43.920
The chicks dig it.

00:03:43.920 --> 00:03:46.180
And I worked on the
school newspaper,

00:03:46.180 --> 00:03:48.620
and I had a really
good English teacher.

00:03:48.620 --> 00:03:51.310
And her name was Mrs. Garrett.

00:03:51.310 --> 00:03:53.630
Are there any teachers
here today?

00:03:53.630 --> 00:03:56.880
Teachers, you have the power.

00:03:56.880 --> 00:03:58.630
Let's give a round of
applause for teachers.

00:03:58.630 --> 00:04:00.820
They don't get enough
love in this country.

00:04:00.820 --> 00:04:05.410
Let's hear it for teachers
because Mrs. Garrett,

00:04:05.410 --> 00:04:08.270
my own goal, whenever we
did a homework assignment,

00:04:08.270 --> 00:04:11.870
I wanted to make Mrs. Garrett
laugh, because I wanted to write

00:04:11.870 --> 00:04:14.150
like Art Buchwald or
Dave Berry or somebody,

00:04:14.150 --> 00:04:15.450
just to make her laugh.

00:04:15.450 --> 00:04:19.560
And she liked my essay so much
that she wrote in the margins

00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:23.120
of one of my papers, you
will make your living

00:04:23.120 --> 00:04:25.080
as a writer someday.

00:04:25.080 --> 00:04:28.680
And when a teacher tells you
something, you know it has

00:04:28.680 --> 00:04:32.090
to be true, because teachers
everywhere, take a solemn vow

00:04:32.090 --> 00:04:33.740
to never ever lie to children.

00:04:33.740 --> 00:04:35.040
Isn't that right teachers,

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:36.340
you all remember
that day in college.

00:04:36.340 --> 00:04:37.640
You had to raise
your right hand.

00:04:37.640 --> 00:04:40.060
Plus, you know, my parents,
if they said, oh Chris,

00:04:40.060 --> 00:04:43.820
you're so talented, you could
be a writer, I would have said,

00:04:43.820 --> 00:04:45.750
you're my mother and
father, you get paid

00:04:45.750 --> 00:04:47.350
to say nice things about me.

00:04:47.350 --> 00:04:49.970
But when a teacher tells
you something, you go,

00:04:49.970 --> 00:04:51.440
ooh, maybe that's true.

00:04:51.440 --> 00:04:53.230
Maybe I've got a little talent.

00:04:53.230 --> 00:04:56.900
So by eighth grade I had
made up my mind that I wanted

00:04:56.900 --> 00:04:59.350
to be a writer when I grew
up, and I can prove it,

00:04:59.350 --> 00:05:02.790
because my mother saved my
eighth grade composition book,

00:05:02.790 --> 00:05:04.740
and every year when
I was in school,

00:05:04.740 --> 00:05:06.750
we had to write the same essay.

00:05:06.750 --> 00:05:09.500
What do you want to
be when you grow up?

00:05:09.500 --> 00:05:12.220
And I used to say I wanted
to be a doctor or a lawyer

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:15.700
or a chemical engineer like my
father, but in eighth grade,

00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:19.680
inspired by my seventh grade
teacher, this is what I wrote.

00:05:19.680 --> 00:05:24.110
But now my mind wanders to a
new thought, to be a comedian

00:05:24.110 --> 00:05:26.690
or a writer is my quest.

00:05:26.690 --> 00:05:31.340
If this flops, I would be
content to be a millionaire

00:05:31.340 --> 00:05:33.900
and run Grabenstein's
department stores

00:05:33.900 --> 00:05:37.510
if I could ever fit
the name on a sign.

00:05:37.510 --> 00:05:38.810
Got a B plus on that.

00:05:38.810 --> 00:05:40.640
I'm looking for a
retroactive A minus at least.

00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:42.970
I got a B plus on that.

00:05:42.970 --> 00:05:46.060
So now, I am living
my eighth grade dream.

00:05:46.060 --> 00:05:47.520
These are all the
books I've written

00:05:47.520 --> 00:05:50.060
so far for guys your age.

00:05:50.060 --> 00:05:51.510
I start out writing a bunch

00:05:51.510 --> 00:05:55.190
of ghost stories called
the haunted mystery series.

00:05:55.190 --> 00:05:57.380
And then I wrote the
island of Dr. Libris.

00:05:57.380 --> 00:05:58.980
Some of you have read
the island of Dr. Libris,

00:05:58.980 --> 00:06:00.550
that's one of my favorite.

00:06:00.550 --> 00:06:02.770
And then this guy named
James Patterson called up.

00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:04.370
He needed a little
help and said,

00:06:04.370 --> 00:06:05.860
could you help me
write a couple books.

00:06:05.860 --> 00:06:07.200
And I said, yeah, sure
Jim, what the heck.

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:11.780
He was actually, James Patterson
and I go way back to 1984.

00:06:11.780 --> 00:06:14.300
He was my first boss
in advertising

00:06:14.300 --> 00:06:16.850
at the Jay Walter Thompson
Advertising Agency.

00:06:16.850 --> 00:06:20.320
So before we wrote about
treasure hunters or funny kids

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:22.020
or houses filled with robots,

00:06:22.020 --> 00:06:25.730
we wrote about flame broiled
whoppers for Burger King.

00:06:25.730 --> 00:06:27.030
Good times, good times.

00:06:27.030 --> 00:06:29.260
So we've got I think
22 books tog,

00:06:29.260 --> 00:06:31.240
and some of you have read Escape

00:06:31.240 --> 00:06:34.000
from Mr. Lemoncello's
Library, is that right?

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:35.570
Ooh, thank you.

00:06:35.570 --> 00:06:37.040
Any of you from Virginia,

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:39.090
because it won a book
award in Virginia.

00:06:39.090 --> 00:06:40.670
So, thank you all,
you Virginians.

00:06:40.670 --> 00:06:42.240
Thank you very much.

00:06:42.240 --> 00:06:47.310
And that book was turned
into a movie on Nickelodeon.

